`nvim/lua/steno-ts/` is a single-file plugin: it is the runtime consumer of the fence protocol and precompiled snippet table produced by this repo's TypeScript compiler (`src/snippet.ts`), turning Plover's sentinel-wrapped stroke tokens into expanded LSP snippets as the user types. Depending on this directory gets you `M.setup(opts)` — call it once with `opts.snippets_path` — and nothing else; there is no public API beyond setup, the two `_`-prefixed test hooks, and the autocmds it installs.

Everything lives in `init.lua`; there is no internal cross-file coupling to describe, only the external coupling to `src/snippet.ts` already noted in that file's `.ctx` (identical `"@@"` sentinel, identical JSON snippet-table shape). A change to the fence format or the JSON schema on the TS side must be mirrored here or expansion silently stops working — the plugin fails closed (no error) on stale JSON, missing snippets, or pre-0.10 Neovim, so breakage here manifests as "nothing happens" rather than a visible error.

No intent.md is present for this directory to check against.